//mineral properties This represents the mineral in powdered form. It is found when a mineral is pulled across an unglazed porcelain streak plate. The color of this mark is what is used as streak. This is the physical appearance of a mineral. You can find this property by simply observing your mineral. A hand lens can be helpful. This is the resistance of a mineral to scratching. This property is described relative to a standard scale of 10 minerals known as the Mohs scale of hardness Hardness is determined by observing the comparative ease or difficulty with which one mineral is scratched by another or by a steel tool. Luster is how the surface of a mineral reflects light. It is found by observing the surface of the mineral. shiny minerals have a metallic luster and non shiny minerals have a non metallic luster Cleavage describes how a crystal breaks when subject to stress on a particular plane. Angle of cleavage is determined by observing the intersection of cleavage planes. Fracture refers to rough or irregular surfaces along which the mineral breaks randomly. This can be found by observing the way in which a mineral breaks in directions other than along cleavage planes. This is the ratio of a minerals mass to its volume. Density of a mineral is found by dividing the mass or weight of a sample by its volume.
//rock properties This describes the minerals that makeup a rock. Mineral composition of a rock is determined by observing the different types of minerals that are present in the rock. Rock texture describes the size, shape, and arrangement of the grains or crystals. Texture can be determined by looking at a rock under a microscope.
